<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900925-0082</DOCNO><DOCID>900925-0082.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   GM Kills the Goose   After Egging It On</HL><DATE>09/25/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A23</SO><CO>   GM LABOR</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><LP>   Regarding your Aug. 29 page-one article &quot;Credibility Gap:UAW and Big Three Face Mutual Mistrust as Auto Talks Heat Up&quot;on General Motors Corp.'s actions at the Flint, Mich.,truck-body parts stamping plant: Can management at that plantbe deemed anything but stupid?   Management obviously had no conception of the optimumproduction rate of its manpower or equipment. It gave itsemployees an incentive to maximize production. When theemployees doubled the production rate, according to thearticle, and held the labor cost constant, managementrewarded the employees by paying them half as much fordoubled production. Is this not known as killing the goosethat laid the golden egg?</LP><TEXT>   Could this stupidity be why it takes six more man-hoursfor GM to produce a car than it does at Japanese plants?   Ervin E. Frauenhoff   Former Stamping Press Operator   Los Angeles</TEXT></DOC>